      <h1 class="hero-title">Healthcare in Bermuda</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        What expats need to know about mandatory insurance, the island's one public hospital,
        private supplemental cover, and when specialist care means travelling.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- REQUIRED disclaimer above the fold -->
      <Disclaimer variant="relocation" />

      <!-- Honest framing -->
      <p style="margin-top: var(--space-6);">
        Bermuda's healthcare system is well-regarded for a small island, and the mandatory insurance
        framework means that everyone in employment has baseline coverage from day one. The honest
        caveat: Bermuda is not a major city. Some specialists are not available locally, a handful of
        conditions require medical travel to the United States, Canada, or the United Kingdom, and
        the single public hospital has the capacity constraints you would expect from a 62,000-person
        population. Understanding the system before you arrive matters.
      </p>

      <!-- SHB mandate -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">1. The Standard Health Benefit (SHB) — mandatory for all residents</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>Standard Health Benefit (SHB)</strong> is mandatory insurance coverage required
        under the Health Insurance Act 1970 for all persons ordinarily resident in Bermuda. It covers
        a defined schedule of hospital and medical services, including emergency care, inpatient
        treatment at King Edward VII Memorial Hospital, and certain outpatient services.
      </p>
      <p>
        The SHB is not a government health service — it is a minimum insurance standard that must be
        provided by a licensed insurer. You cannot opt out.
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <div class="table-wrapper">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Item</th>
                <th>Detail</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>SHB rate</td>
                <td>
                  <strong>$400.31 per adult per month</strong>
                  <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-10" sourceLabel="Bermuda Health Council (bhec.bm)" sourceUrl="https://www.bhec.bm" />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Employer contribution</td>
                <td>Employers are required by law to contribute at least 50% of the SHB premium for employees on work permits</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Coverage scope</td>
                <td>Hospital inpatient, emergency treatment, certain outpatient services — not dental, optical, or most specialist care</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
