        </div>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        <span class="unverified">[Employer contribution rules — verify current requirements with your employer and at bhec.bm before arriving. Rules change with the annual Budget.]</span>
      </p>

      <!-- KEMH -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">2. King Edward VII Memorial Hospital (KEMH)</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>King Edward VII Memorial Hospital</strong> in Pembroke Parish is Bermuda's only public
        hospital. It is the primary facility for emergency care, surgery, inpatient treatment, and
        most specialist outpatient clinics. For a facility serving a small island population, it
        is well-equipped for general and emergency medicine.
      </p>
      <p>
        KEMH has an Accident and Emergency department, operating theatres, an Intensive Care Unit,
        maternity services, and a range of specialist clinics — cardiology, oncology, orthopaedics,
        and others. It is run by the Bermuda Hospitals Board, a quasi-governmental body.
      </p>
      <p>
        The honest note on capacity: wait times at A&amp;E can be long by the standards of a large
        urban hospital. Non-emergency specialist appointments often have meaningful wait times.
        Many expats use the private medical facilities — GP practices, private clinics — for routine
        and non-emergency care precisely to avoid the public hospital queue for minor matters.
      </p>

      <!-- Private supplemental insurance -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">3. Supplemental insurance — what most employers provide</h2>
      <p>
        The SHB covers the baseline, but the gaps are significant: dental, optical, prescription
        drugs beyond the SHB formulary, private room hospitalisation, specialist consultations,
        and medical evacuation are not included in the standard benefit.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most employers in Bermuda's international business sector provide supplemental health
        insurance above the SHB as a standard employment benefit. This top-up plan typically
        fills the major gaps and may include private room cover at KEMH, extended outpatient
        benefits, and medical evacuation cover for cases requiring overseas treatment.
      </p>
      <p>
        The two main health insurance providers in Bermuda:
      </p>
      <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <li>
          <strong>Argus Group</strong> (<a href="https://www.argus.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">argus.bm</a>) —
          one of the two dominant providers, offering a range of group and individual health plans
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>BF&amp;M</strong> (<a href="https://www.bfm.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">bfm.bm</a>) —
          the other major provider; most large employers use either Argus or BF&amp;M for their
          group health plans
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>Before negotiating your employment package:</strong> ask specifically what supplemental
        health plan is included, what the employee contribution is (many employers cover the full
        premium; some split it), and whether it covers dependants. Do not assume the SHB alone
        is adequate for a family.
      </p>

      <!-- Specialist care / medical tourism -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">4. Specialist care and medical tourism</h2>
      <p>
        Some medical specialties are not available locally or have limited local capacity. Certain
        complex surgical procedures, sub-specialist oncology, advanced cardiac intervention, and
        some paediatric specialties may require referral overseas — typically to the United States
        (Johns Hopkins, Cleveland Clinic, and Boston-area hospitals are common referral destinations),
        or in some cases to the United Kingdom or Canada.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a known and planned-for feature of healthcare on a small island, not a failure of
        the system. A well-structured supplemental insurance plan will include
        <strong>medical evacuation cover</strong> — the policy provision that covers the cost of
        emergency medical transport to an overseas facility. Confirm whether your employer's plan
        includes this and what the geographic coverage is before you move.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        <span class="unverified">[Specific referral arrangements and available specialties — verify with KEMH and your insurer; they change as staffing changes.]</span>
      </p>

      <!-- Dental -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">5. Dental care</h2>
      <p>
        Dental treatment is not covered by the SHB baseline. Bermuda has private dental practices
        in Hamilton and across the island, and the quality of care is generally good. Costs are
        comparable to or slightly above US private dental rates.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most employer supplemental plans include a dental benefit with annual limits — typically
        $1,500–2,500 per person per year for preventive and restorative care. Orthodontics and
        cosmetic work are usually excluded or sub-limited. Check your plan's dental schedule carefully.
      </p>

      <!-- Mental health -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">6. Mental health resources</h2>
      <p>
        KEMH has a psychiatric unit (the Mid-Atlantic Wellness Institute, known as MWI) providing
        inpatient psychiatric services. Outpatient mental health services are available through
        a mix of private therapists and counsellors and the public system.
      </p>
      <p>
        The availability of therapists in Bermuda is more limited than in a major city — waiting
        times for non-urgent appointments can be longer than you might be used to.
        Telehealth options (US or UK-licensed therapists via video) are used by some expats as a
        supplement. Confirm whether your health plan covers telehealth with an overseas provider
        if this is a consideration.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>Employee Assistance Programme (EAP)</strong> is offered by some employers and
        provides confidential short-term counselling. Ask HR whether your employer provides this.
      </p>

      <!-- Authoritative source -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-ink); color: var(--color-white); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-top: var(--space-10);">
